Taking an assumption, you are probably using your WiFi on your laptop to connect to the robot. This means you don’t have access to an internet connected WiFi network. You can either run a build while connected to a WiFi network to cache the dependencies, and then connect to the robot and run a deploy, or you can purchase a WiFi dongle for ~$10. The dongle will give your computer 2 WiFi networks, so you can connect to the robot and the internet at the same time.

I see you already resolved this, but I want to chime in because I’ve seen this same error many times for different reasons.

  1. The most common reason is you are connected to the robot’s wifi and not to the Internet. Solution is to disconnect from the robot and connect to the internet and run a build. After the files are downloaded, you should be able to run build while connected only to the robot.

  2. One of the urls is being blocked by your firewall or DNS resolver. I ran into this a few years back and it turned out the school was blocking a domain that one of the maven packages was hosted on, breaking the build. Turns out the school firewall was only blocking wifi connections, and by using a wired connection I was able to successfully download and build without having to leave school. YMMV on this problem and solution.

  3. less frequently, the URL no longer hosts the software package. This happened at least once when the maven repository was removed. Not likely for Rev Robotics or CTRE, but a possibility for some 3rd party packages. In that case, manually check the URLs the build process says it cannot download.

  4. HTTPS errors. I have seen few cases where whatever process is fetching the package decides that the HTTPS certificate is not valid and refuses to download the package. This should show up in the error message. Again, try to manually confirm the package URL.

I have found that connecting to the Internet via a wired connection (USB to Ethernet adapter) and simultaneously to the robot via wifi is a very convenient way to work. This way when you try to do a google search on some error, open some documentation, message someone on the team, or stream your programming session you can while also being connected to the robot and deploying code and running the driver station. No more switching between robot and internet wifi.
